                <div2>
                    <head>
                        <title type="main">
                            <hi rend="b">TRICKSTER’S SONG</hi>
                        </title>
                    </head>
                    <p>After reading E. B. Murray’s “<hi rend="i">Jerusalem</hi>
                        Reversed” in <hi rend="i">Blake Studies</hi> vol. 7 no. 1, I opened my
                        copy of Blake—conscious of imitating Blake’s use of
                        Bysshe—and began reading “The Voice of the Ancient Bard” as
                        “in a mirror, darkly.” The result is not the finest poetry, but
                        note the energy of Blake’s words is not destroyed and in some cases
                        is enhanced with new meaning: “Her perplex roots tangled / there!”
                        This is not meant as an example of extending Murray’s criticism or of
                        promoting a Cabbalistic dabbling in Blake’s good book—just one
                        poet’s playful response to England’s greatest.</p>
					<q> Videmus nunc per speculum in aenigmate . . .<lb/>
 Paul, I Corinthians
                        13:12<lb/>
                        <lb/>
 Hither comes delight of youth,<lb/>
 morn opening to see.
                        And<lb/>
 born new truth of Image.<lb/>
                        <lb/>
 Reason of clouds!<lb/>
 And fled
                        is doubt<lb/>
 teasing artful, and dispute’s dark<lb/>
 maze. Endless
                        is folly’s<lb/>
 way. Her perplex roots tangled<lb/>
                        <lb/>
 there!
                        Fallen have many how<lb/>
 dead, the bones over night.<lb/>
 All stumble.
                        They<lb/>
 care but what not know they feel. And<lb/>
 be led, should they?
                        When others lead. Wish.<lb/>
 And </q>
